postcontent: Selling my STG-58 FAL style rifle. This is the Austrian version of the FAL, built on an Imbel receiver.   This gun was brought in during the AWB, and thus has no flash hider.  You get what has traditionally been considered the most desirable build receiver in the Imbel with the most desirable Steyr produced Austrian parts kit  Has a top rail mount and a quad rail forearm installed and comes with 1 20 round magazine.  Weapon has less than 100 rounds through it and has functioned perfectly firing Lake City .308 ball. The primary rifle of the U.N. among others for decades, these rifles are incredibly accurate and saw a lot of duty in S. America nad Africa during the Cold War.  It's also a  nice change if you want to have something different in a battle rifle, when everyone else at the range is using a M1A or an AR10, but unlike getting an exotic, these have plenty of surplus parts available.  I will ship the rifle to your FFL if you're not local, but you will be responsible for shipping costs.  I will consider trades (No ARs, and I can get most things I want at wholesale if I want them new) with preference towards longslide 1911s, Ruger .454 Alaskans, .454 Bisley Super Blackhawks and HK P30L and VP series pistols.

title: For Sale/Trade:  WW2 Nazi SS Totenkopf K98 mauser
postcontent: Here is a K98 Mauser that was issued to Hitler's Elite SS troops. It is correctly marked with the two SS skulls on the barrel, one with just SS, one with SS2 over it. The receiver has light markings on it but it is still clear enough to read the 'Amberg 1917' on the receiver. Meaning, this was originally a WW1 Gewehr 98 long barrel rifle. However, when Hitler came into power and began forming his SS he needed newer, more modern rifles. So what they did was rework WW1 mausers into K98 configuration. Many many SS rifles have WW1 receivers. In addition, to hide that they were ramping up their war industry, they refrained from putting SS markings on the receiver, to hide that the rifles were newly manufactured because it was forbiden by the treaty of versailes. This K98 also has a star at the wrist of the stock, which is another signature SS K98 marking. Over the time SS or skull above/under the star has mostly faded and I cannot distinguish it out. On this rifle the numbers don't match, as there are few numbers at all. But the stock is in great condition. Has a reinforcing stock lug as you can see in the photos. This rifle comes with a cleaning rod, and has many WW1 Gew 98 pieces on it, which is correct for this rifle. The bore has strong rifling and no visible pitting, though it is dark. I suspect a good scrubbing will brighten it back up. There are no import markings on this rifle.Will entertain trades, however cash is preferred.
